{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"# Pin the release supply chain to immutable references\n\nMake every executable the release depends on identifiable by an immutable\nreference: full-SHA action pins, a hash-locked build environment, an\nexact-versioned + digest-verified MCP publisher, and non-persisted checkout\ncredentials. (Readiness Finding 4 — verified VALID against `release.yml`\nlines 31/32/43/60/65/85/124/129 and `pyproject.toml:1-3`.)\n\n## Why\n\nTwo release runs of the same rebar SHA can execute different build/upload/publish\ncode today. `release.yml` references first-party actions by moving major-version\ntags (`actions/checkout@v7` at :31/:124, `actions/setup-python@v6` at :32,\n`actions/upload-artifact@v7` at :43, `actions/download-artifact@v8` at :60/:85);\ninstalls build tools with unrestricted upgrades (`pip install --upgrade build`\n:37, `--upgrade twine` :41); publishes via the branch-like `pypa/gh-action-pypi-publish@release/v1`\n(:65); declares the build backend as bare `hatchling` (`pyproject.toml:1-3`); and\nin the `mcp_registry` job downloads its publisher from a mutable `releases/latest`\nURL and executes it **without a digest/signature check** (:129) in a job that holds\n`id-token: write` (used for GitHub OIDC login + registry publication). None of the\ncheckouts set `persist-credentials: false`, so the token persists in local git\nconfig by default. The repo already SHA-pins **third-party** actions in\n`gerrit-verify.yaml` (per its header comment); this story extends that practice to\n`release.yml`'s first-party `actions/*` uses, which are still tag-pinned.\n\n## What\n\nAdopt the uv / pip pinning pattern (uv: full-SHA action pins, `persist-credentials:\nfalse`, a pinned release tool with a verified SHA-256; pip: SHA-pinned actions +\na hash-locked build environment installed with `--require-hashes --no-deps`):\n\n- Replace each action tag with a full commit SHA, keeping the human-readable\n  version in a trailing comment.\n- Set `persist-credentials: false` on every release checkout unless a later git\n  operation demonstrably needs the persisted credential.\n- Create a reviewed release lock/constraints file covering `build`, Hatchling,\n  Twine, any artifact-validation tools, and their transitive deps, generated and\n  maintained with an established tool — **`pip-compile --generate-hashes` (pip-tools)**\n  (or `uv pip compile --generate-hashes`) — checked into the repo.\n- **Hatchling enforcement — decision.** pip's default `python -m build` resolves the\n  `[build-system]` requires in a *fresh isolated env*, so the lock only governs\n  Hatchling's version if the build uses the pre-installed locked env. **This story\n  uses `--no-build-isolation`**: pre-install the hash-locked env (including Hatchling)\n  with `pip install --require-hashes -r <lock>`, then `python -m build\n  --no-build-isolation`. This keeps enforcement entirely in the workflow and avoids\n  editing `pyproject.toml` `[build-system]`. A workflow lint/test step fails if\n  `--no-build-isolation` is absent (so no free-resolution path can silently return).\n- **MCP publisher — download → verify → execute (never stream into tar).** Replace\n  the `releases/latest` URL with an exact version, and split the current\n  `curl … | tar xz` one-liner into three ordered steps so an unverified archive is\n  never extracted or executed:\n  1. `curl -fsSL \"<exact-version-url>\" -o mcp-publisher.tar.gz`\n  2. `echo \"<pinned-sha256>  mcp-publisher.tar.gz\" | sha256sum -c --strict`\n  3. `tar xzf mcp-publisher.tar.gz mcp-publisher`\n  Prefer an upstream `checksums.txt` if `modelcontextprotocol/registry` ships one;\n  otherwise hard-code the SHA-256 computed at pin time with a rationale comment.\n  **Arch note:** the current download URL is built from `uname -s`/`uname -m`, so the\n  `<url, sha256>` pair is arch-specific. `release.yml` runs on `ubuntu-latest`\n  (linux/amd64), so pin the `linux_amd64` URL + its SHA-256 as a single deliberate\n  pair (documented, with a revisit note if the runner arch changes); store one pair\n  per supported OS/arch tuple if the matrix ever expands.\n  **Security contract — structural job split (not step ordering).** In GitHub\n  Actions `id-token: write` is a *job-level* permission: the OIDC token endpoint\n  (`$ACTIONS_ID_TOKEN_REQUEST_URL`) is reachable from the job's **first** step, so\n  step ordering within one job does NOT prevent a compromised archive from minting a\n  token during the download step. Enforce co-residency structurally by **splitting\n  the job in two**: `mcp_verify` (no `id-token: write`; runs curl download +\n  `sha256sum -c` and uploads the verified binary as an artifact / sets a `verified`\n  output) and `mcp_registry` (`needs: mcp_verify`; holds `id-token: write`; consumes\n  the already-verified artifact and runs `mcp-publisher login`/`publish`). Fail on an\n  unexpected filename/size/digest/version. So the OIDC-privileged job never downloads\n  or holds an unverified binary.\n- Print and retain in release evidence: every action SHA, the Python build-tool\n  versions, the MCP publisher version + downloaded digest, and the wheel/sdist digests.\n- Update pins through reviewed dependency-update changes, not implicit resolution\n  during a production release.\n\n## Scope\n\n- `.github/workflows/release.yml` — SHA-pin all `uses:`; `persist-credentials:\n  false`; `--no-build-isolation` hash-locked build install; split the MCP publisher\n  into an unprivileged `mcp_verify` job + an OIDC-privileged `mcp_registry` job that\n  consumes the verified artifact (coordinate with Findings 1 and 3, which also edit\n  this file).\n- A new release build lock/constraints file (e.g. under `.github/` or `requirements/`).\n- `pyproject.toml` — **no change** to `[build-system]` requires: with the chosen\n  `--no-build-isolation` strategy the Hatchling version is governed by the\n  pre-installed hash-locked env, not by `pyproject.toml` (this is deliberate; if the\n  isolated-build path were kept instead, a `[build-system]` pin would be required —\n  but it is not kept).\n- `docs/releasing.md` — document the pinning policy and the pin-update process.\n  **Section ownership:** this story owns the \"Pinning\" section only (Finding 1 owns\n  \"Release-source authorization\", Finding 3 owns \"Build-once\"), avoiding overlap\n  across the three concurrent release stories.\n- Out of scope: pinning non-release workflows already SHA-pinned; full reproducible\n  builds (covered adjacent to Finding 3).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Every `uses:` in `release.yml` references a full 40-char commit SHA with a\n  trailing version comment — verified by a workflow-lint/grep check (extendable from\n  the repo's existing SHA-pin convention in `gerrit-verify.yaml`) that fails if any\n  `uses:` in `release.yml` is a tag/branch rather than a 40-hex SHA.\n- [ ] Every release checkout sets `persist-credentials: false` — verified by the\n  same workflow-lint step used for the SHA-pin check, which also greps every\n  `actions/checkout` block in `release.yml` for `persist-credentials: false` and\n  fails if it is absent.\n- [ ] Release build tools (`build`, Hatchling, Twine, validation tools) install from\n  a reviewed hash-locked file (generated by `pip-compile --generate-hashes`) with\n  `--require-hashes` — verified by a CI step that, against the already-installed\n  environment, runs `pip install --dry-run --require-hashes --no-deps -r <lock>` and\n  asserts it exits zero (every installed version satisfies the locked hashes); the\n  install step also emits `pip list --format=freeze > tool-versions.txt` into the\n  release evidence artifact.\n- [ ] Hatchling's version is enforced end-to-end via `--no-build-isolation` against\n  the pre-installed hash-locked env (not via a `pyproject.toml` pin), with a workflow\n  lint/test step that fails if `--no-build-isolation` is removed (no free-resolution\n  path remains).\n- [ ] The MCP publisher is pinned to an exact version and its archive digest is\n  verified in a separate `mcp_verify` job that has **no** `id-token: write`; the\n  OIDC-privileged `mcp_registry` job `needs: mcp_verify` and consumes only the\n  verified artifact — so the OIDC scope is never co-resident with an unverified\n  binary. Verified by a CI job that corrupts one byte of the pinned archive, runs the\n  verify step, and asserts it exits non-zero. If upstream ships no checksums, the\n  pinned SHA-256 is hard-coded in the workflow with a rationale comment.\n- [ ] Release evidence records action SHAs, build-tool versions, and the MCP\n  publisher version + verified digest — each written by a named workflow step into a\n  single evidence artifact (e.g. `release-evidence.txt`): the SHA-pin lint dumps\n  resolved action SHAs, the build step appends `tool-versions.txt`, and the\n  `mcp_verify` step appends the publisher version + verified digest. (Wheel/sdist\n  SHA-256 sums are added to the same evidence artifact by Finding 3's build-once\n  step, which lands **after** this story — this story is the head of the release\n  chain — so they are out of scope here and not a prerequisite for this AC.)\n- [ ] `docs/releasing.md` documents the pinning policy and pin-update process.\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && make test` pass, and the change lands via the\n  Gerrit two-vote gate."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784051638240894001,"uuid":"4d97e9dd-c498-485b-8a0c-f1eac7afc9cc"}